That’s one of the most enduring ideas in science and philosophy, and it’s surprisingly compatible with a lot of modern biology.

A human body replaces much of its material over time.

The atoms change.

The molecules change.

The food comes and goes.

The air comes and goes.

The water comes and goes.

And yet something persists.

Not the substance.

The organization.

The pattern.

This connects directly to a doctrine you’ve already stored:

Structure stores possibility; flow expresses it.

A whirlpool is a classic example.

The water isn’t the whirlpool.

The water flows through it.

The whirlpool is the pattern imposed upon the flow.

Life looks remarkably similar in some respects.

Cells die.

Proteins are replaced.

Energy enters and leaves.

Yet the organism maintains a coherent structure through time.

That’s why many biologists describe life less as a thing and more as a process.

Not:

a static object

but

a self-maintaining pattern of energy, matter, information, repair, and adaptation.

Which echoes your “Life as Energy-Flow Geometry” doctrine almost exactly.

The interesting part is that once you start viewing life this way, many apparent opposites become complements:

* DNA stores structure; metabolism provides flow.
* Memory stores patterns; experience updates them.
* Culture stores patterns; people express them.
* Code stores logic; execution expresses it.

The chiasm almost writes itself:

Structure shapes flow.

…

Flow reshapes structure.

And life exists in that crossing.

Where I’d be careful is not to collapse everything into “it’s all patterns.” That’s true in one sense, but sometimes too much compression loses useful distinctions.

A hurricane is a pattern.

A crystal is a pattern.

A market is a pattern.

A language is a pattern.

A living cell is a pattern.

They’re all patterns—but they’re not the same kind of pattern.

Life appears special because it doesn’t merely persist.

It:

* repairs itself,
* reproduces,
* adapts,
* learns,
* maintains boundaries,
* and extracts order from its environment.

So if I were to compress your thought into a single sentence, I’d probably say:

Life is not matter; life is the continuing pattern that matter temporarily agrees to perform.